00:16:19.090 --> 00:16:22.000 align:middle line:10%
And you can see that when
eccentricity, for example,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000 align:middle line:10%
and obliquity, when
those coincide,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:26.965 align:middle line:10%
we have a warming
period on the Earth.

00:16:26.965 --> 00:16:28.840 align:middle line:10%
I'm showing you this on
the screen right now.

00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:30.631 align:middle line:10%
And you say, well,
maybe that's an anomaly.

00:16:30.631 --> 00:16:32.325 align:middle line:10%
Maybe it's just that one time.

00:16:32.325 --> 00:16:33.125 align:middle line:10%
But look at this.

00:16:33.125 --> 00:16:35.400 align:middle line:10%
If we go back and
look at each of these.

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:38.750 align:middle line:10%
Here we're seeing
eccentricity as a peak

00:16:38.750 --> 00:16:40.570 align:middle line:10%
and we're also seeing
obliquity as a peak

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:41.740 align:middle line:10%
in the blue and the green.

00:16:41.740 --> 00:16:42.760 align:middle line:10%
and right below that.

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:46.290 align:middle line:10%
Every place where that happened,
we saw warming in our planet.

00:16:46.290 --> 00:16:48.640 align:middle line:10%
And it happens all the time.

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:52.570 align:middle line:10%
So the reason this is important
is because we are here

00:16:52.570 --> 00:16:54.580 align:middle line:10%
at the far left of the screen.

00:16:54.580 --> 00:16:56.980 align:middle line:10%
Where that red
