00:17:12.849 --> 00:17:16.210 align:middle line:84%
And we are seeing a
relatively small warming

00:17:16.210 --> 00:17:18.770 align:middle line:84%
compared to what we
have seen in the past.

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:21.760 align:middle line:84%
So this is one of
the cycles, climate.

00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:25.359 align:middle line:84%
And I mentioned there are three
cycles that are converging.

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:29.377 align:middle line:84%
I spent a little bit
more time on this portion

00:17:29.377 --> 00:17:31.210 align:middle line:84%
because we're hearing
so much about climate.

00:17:31.210 --> 00:17:32.709 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
important to really

00:17:32.709 --> 00:17:34.151 align:middle line:84%
understand throughout
this series,

00:17:34.151 --> 00:17:35.650 align:middle line:84%
throughout "Missing
Links" I'm going

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:39.010 align:middle line:84%
to refer back to the
extremes that are

00:17:39.010 --> 00:17:41.140 align:middle line:90%
being caused by these cycles.

00:17:41.140 --> 00:17:43.750 align:middle line:84%
The second cycle that
I'd like to talk to you

00:17:43.750 --> 00:17:47.182 align:middle line:90%
about is the cycle of economies.

00:17:47.182 --> 00:17:48.640 align:middle line:84%
And when I talk
about economies, it

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:49.750 align:middle line:90%
doesn't have to be about money.

00:17:49.750 --> 00:17:50.720 align:middle line:90%
It can be.

00:17:50.720 --> 00:17:53.470 align:middle line:84%
The economies are about
people, about the way

00:17:53.470 --> 00:17:56.440 align:middle line:84%
we work together and share
the vital resources that we

00:17:56.440 --> 00:17:59.040 align:middle line:90%
need-- food, water, medicine.

00:17:59.040 --> 00:18:02.870 align:middle line:10%
Well there was an economist
early in the 20th century.

00:18:02.870 --> 00:18:07.270 align:middle line:10%
His name was Nikolai
Kondratiev, Nikolai Kondratiev.

00:18:07.270 --> 00:18:12.760 align:middle line:10%
And he was the first to
recognize the rhythm of cycles

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:15.820 align:middle line:10%
as it plays out in global
and local economies.

00:18:15.820 --> 00:18:18.460 align:middle line:84%
Whether we're talking the
small scale of a family,

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:20.540 align:middle line:84%
or a large scale the
community, or a planet,

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:21.790 align:middle line:90%
it seems to be the same thing.

00:18:21.790 --> 00:18:26.320 align:middle line:84%
And what he did is he identified
a 66-year economic cycle.

00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:28.375 align:middle line:84%
And he broke this
cycle into seasons.

00:18:28.375 --> 00:18:30.560 align:middle line:90%
And I find this fascinating.

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:35.470 align:middle line:84%
Our 66-year cycle, that we're
in right now began in 1949.

00:18:35.470 --> 00:18:39.550 align:middle line:10%
That was what he called the
Spring of this economic cycle.

00:18:39.550 --> 00:18:46.840 align:middle line:10%
And it lasted from 1949
until the year 1966.

00:18:46.840 --> 00:18:48.550 align:middle line:10%
This was a time of inflation.

00:18:48.550 --> 00:18:51.010 align:middle line:10%
It was a beginning of
an inflationary cycle.

00:18:51.010 --> 00:18:52.630 align:middle line:10%
And in inflation,
as we all know,

00:18:52.630 --> 00:18:55.300 align:middle line:10%
there are certain stocks,
certain commodities,

00:18:55.300 --> 00:18:59.200 align:middle line:10%
certain bonds, that that
tend to do better or worse

00:18:59.200 --> 00:19:01.930 align:middle line:10%
depending on where
we are in this cycle.

00:19:01.930 --> 00:19:04.480 align:middle line:10%
In the inflationary
cycle, what we see is

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:07.690 align:middle line:10%
there are certain assets that
tend to do better in the Spring

00:19:07.690 --> 00:19:09.460 align:middle line:10%
than they do in other times.

00:19:09.460 --> 00:19:12.520 align:middle line:84%
But the Spring only
lasted until 1966.

00:19:12.520 --> 00:19:16.660 align:middle line:10%
From 1966 until
the year 1980, we

00:19:16.660 --> 00:19:20.020 align:middle line:10%
were in the Summer of
this economic cycle.

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:21.970 align:middle line:90%
And I remember this personally.

00:19:21.970 --> 00:19:26.680 align:middle line:84%
I was in school and I was
working in the 1960s, 1970s.

00:19:26.680 --> 00:19:29.290 align:middle line:84%
I remember when I could
deposit my paycheck in the bank

00:19:29.290 --> 00:19:33.040 align:middle line:84%
and I could get 16, 17,
18% interest on my money

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:38.020 align:middle line:84%
because we were in an economic
cycle of this inflation.

00:19:38.020 --> 00:19:39.710 align:middle line:90%
It was called runaway inflation.

00:19:39.710 --> 00:19:40.510 align:middle line:90%
It was good for me.

00:19:40.510 --> 00:19:42.700 align:middle line:10%
It helped me to
save for college.

00:19:42.700 --> 00:19:45.730 align:middle line:10%
so that's something we may
not see again for a while.

00:19:45.730 --> 00:19:51.220 align:middle line:10%
So from 1980, we went into a
new economic cycle, the Autumn,

00:19:51.220 --> 00:19:54.250 align:middle line:10%
that lasts until the year 2000.

00:19:54.250 --> 00:19:55.720 align:middle line:10%
And in this cycle,
as the others,

00:19:55.720 --> 00:19:57.880 align:middle line:10%
there are certain investments.

00:19:57.880 --> 00:20:00.670 align:middle line:10%
There are certain
tangible assets

00:20:00.670 --> 00:20:02.200 align:middle line:10%
that seem to do
better in this cycle

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:04.990 align:middle line:10%
than they do in
others until we enter

00:20:04.990 --> 00:20:07.240 align:middle line:10%
into the next
phase of the cycle.

00:20:07.240 --> 00:20:12.100 align:middle line:10%
In the year 2000, we went into
the Winter of the 66-year cycle

00:20:12.100 --> 00:20:13.100 align:middle line:10%
that we're in right now.

00:20:13.100 --> 00:20:16.730 align:middle line:10%
A period that is
less popularly known.

00:20:16.730 --> 00:20:20.380 align:middle line:10%
It's called dis-inflation
or deflation,

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:23.620 align:middle line:10%
when the things that used to
have value begin to lose value.

00:20:23.620 --> 00:20:24.860 align:middle line:90%
Property loses value.

00:20:24.860 --> 00:20:27.200 align:middle line:84%
Precious metals
lose their value.

